Discovery II GE Control notes:

Based on the MAC destination address (DA), a queue is determined:
  If the DA is a unicast MAC address, and the upper 44 bits match with
  programmed MAC address for the port (defined in
  MAC Address Low Register MACAL, MAC Address High Register MACAH),
  then the lower 4 bits in DA are used to look up the DA-Filter Unicast Table
  to determine pass/drop and queue number.

  If the DA is a multicast MAC address of the form 0x01-00-5E-00-00-XX,
  then the lowest 8 bits of DA are used to look up the DA-Filter Special
  Multicast Table (DFSMT) to determine pass/drop and queue number.

  If the DA is a multicast MAC address of other form, an 8-bit CRC
  will be computed based on the polynomial: x^8 + x^2 + x + 1,
  and the result is used to look up the DA-Filter Other Multicast Table (DFOMT).

If the frame is not dropped based on the DA parsing above,
  If it is a TCP frame, TCP_CapEn and TCPQ bits in Port Configuration Register
  (PxCR) is used for the pass/drop and queue number.

  If it is a UDP frame, UDP_CapEn and UDPQ bits in Port Configuration Register
  (PxCR) is used for the pass/drop and queue number.

  If it is VLAN tagged, the priority field is used to look up the 
  VLAN Priority Tag to Priority Register (VPT2P) to determine a queue number.

  If it is an IPv4 frame, the DiffServ Code Point (DSCP) is used to look up
  the DSCPx registers to determine a queue number.

The final queue number will be the higest queue number from the DA-Filter
lookup, and protocol/VLAN tag/DSCP lookup.


Note: A MAC address is an multicast address if the least significant bit
      of the first byte is 1.  Otherwise it is a unicast MAC address.

Note: Multicast IP addresses are class D address
      (224.0.0.0 to 239.255.255.255, or start with binary prefix 1110).
      Their corresponding Ethernet MAC address has the prefix 01-00-5e.
      
Note: To map from multicast IP to multicast MAC address, copy lower 23 bits
      of IP to lower 3 bytes in MAC.  Hence each multicast MAC address
      is shared by 32 multicast IP addresses.

Note: 802.1Q specifies a tag in Ethernet MAC frame, with 12 bit VLAN ID
      and 3 bit priority.
      802.1p defines the use of the priority field.
  

